Title: Do not launch desktop helper processes on iOS

## Problem

KConfig uses `QProcess` in two desktop-oriented code paths:

- Running `kconf_update` when checking configuration updates.
- Running `kdialog` when reporting a non-writable configuration.

iOS applications cannot launch arbitrary external processes, and Qt for iOS
does not provide the required `QProcess::execute()` functionality. These calls
therefore prevent KConfig from compiling for iOS.

The referenced helper executables also do not exist in an iOS application
bundle, so retaining these calls would not provide useful runtime behavior.

## Proposed change

Exclude both external-process calls when compiling for iOS. Configuration
parsing and writability detection remain available; only the attempts to invoke
desktop helper programs are disabled.

## Impact

On iOS, KConfig does not automatically execute `kconf_update` and does not show
a `kdialog` warning for non-writable configuration files. Behavior on all
other platforms remains unchanged.

